# **4.  Infrastructure Metrics**

Source: macOS native APIs, Stats (mac-stats.com) for live display, hw_collector.py + hardware_metrics table (ADR-034) for persistent history, pmset, shell queries. All available from setup day (live display) or Phase 1.5 (persistent history). Stats is the recommended live display tool for the hardware layer; hw_collector.py provides the 60-second-resolution PostgreSQL history.

| **Metric** | **Detail / Alert Threshold** | **Display Format** | **Phase** | **NIST** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| THERMALS |
| CPU Temperature | All P-cores + E-cores. Alert > 85°C sustained | Speedometer dial + sparkline 24h | Phase 1 | SI-4 |
| GPU Temperature | Integrated GPU. Alert > 80°C sustained | Speedometer dial + sparkline 24h | Phase 1 | SI-4 |
| Thermal Pressure State | nominal / fair / serious / critical. Maps to m1_thermal_state in ADR-029. Alert on serious or critical. | Traffic light | Phase 1 | AU-3 · SI-4(5) |
| Fan Speed (RPM) | M1 Max has one fan. Log duration above 3000 RPM. Alert if sustained > 30 min. | Speedometer dial + duration counter | Phase 1 | SI-4 |
| System Power Draw | Watts. Idle target: 15–30W. Alert > 80W sustained (indicates thermal stress or runaway process). | Line chart 24h | Phase 1 | SI-4 |
| MEMORY |
| Unified Memory Used / Available | Total 32GB. Critical thresholds: 28GB used = yellow, 30GB = red. | Bar + percentage | Phase 1 | SI-4 |
| Memory Pressure State | macOS green / yellow / red. Yellow = near limit, Red = paging active. | Traffic light | Phase 1 | SI-4(5) |
| Swap Usage | Apple Silicon swap = unified memory overflow. Any swap > 0 = alert. Signals model load exceeds physical RAM. | Badge + alert | Phase 1 | SI-4(5) |
| GPU Memory Pressure | Maps directly to gpu_memory_pressure field in ADR-029 agent_actions schema. | Sparkline per session | Phase 1 | AU-3 · SI-4 |
| Per-Process Memory | Named processes: Ollama, Docker, PostgreSQL, ChromaDB. Track per-model load footprint. | Stacked bar | Phase 1 | SI-4(2) |
| CPU |
| P-Core vs E-Core Utilization | Performance cores vs efficiency cores separately. Ollama inference runs on P-cores. | Dual speedometer gauge | Phase 1 | SI-4 |
| System Load Average | 1-min, 5-min, 15-min. Alert if 15-min load exceeds 8.0 (of 10 P+E cores on M1 Max). | 3-number badge | Phase 1 | SI-4 |
| Ollama Inference Utilization | CPU/GPU % during active model inference. Compare across Tier 1/2/3 model sizes. | Line chart per session | Phase 1 | SI-4(2) |
| STORAGE |
| SSD Used / Available | 512GB total. Alert at 80% used (410GB), critical at 90% (460GB). | Bar + percentage | Phase 1 | AU-4 · SI-4 |
| Mac-Mini-Backups Folder Size | iCloud Drive folder. Alert threshold: 5GB (matches ADR-019 Telegram alert). Track growth trend. | Bar against 5GB threshold | Phase 1 | AU-4 · AU-9 |
| PostgreSQL Data Directory | Track growth rate. Flag if > 5GB/month — informs ADR-031 retention review. | Line chart weekly | Phase 1 | AU-4 |
| ChromaDB Vector Store Size | Per-persona namespace sizes. Track RAG corpus growth. | Stacked bar by persona | Phase 1 | AU-4 |
| Docker Image Cache | Total Docker image storage. Alert if > 30GB — pull accumulation. | Single number | Phase 1 | CM-8 |
| NETWORK |
| Tailscale Interface Throughput | Bytes in/out on Tailscale WireGuard interface. Baseline for anomaly detection. | Line chart 24h + heatmap | Phase 1 | AC-17(1) · SC-7 |
| Active SSH Sessions | Count of active SSH connections via Tailscale. Alert on concurrent count > 1 (single operator). | Badge + count | Phase 1 | AC-17(1) · AU-14 |
| WireGuard Tunnel Status | Up / Down. Alert immediately on tunnel drop — operator access lost. | Traffic light | Phase 1 | SC-7(3) · SI-4(5) |
| Telegram API Connection | OpenClaw Telegram polling status. Alert on disconnect > 5 min. | Traffic light | Phase 1 | SI-4(5) |
| UPTIME AND RECOVERY |
| System Uptime | Days:hours:minutes since last boot. Log all reboot events with timestamps. | Counter + history table | Phase 1 | SI-4 |
| OpenClaw Daemon Uptime | Uptime of openclaw LaunchAgent process. Gap between system uptime and daemon uptime = recovery lag. | Counter + gap indicator | Phase 1 | SI-4(2) · IR-4 |
| Autorestart Events | Count of reboots triggered by pmset autorestart (power failure recovery). Each event = anomaly to investigate. | Count + timestamps | Phase 1 | IR-4 · IR-8 |
| LaunchAgent Start Latency | Time from system boot to OpenClaw daemon running. Baseline this — increases indicate boot-time issues. | Single number per event | Phase 1 | SI-4(2) |

# **5.  Agent Layer Metrics**

Source: PostgreSQL agent_actions table (ADR-029). All 21 fields are observable on Phase 1 setup day. Queries run from the dev account SSH session or via Telegram natural-language queries to the agent.

| **Metric** | **Detail / Alert Threshold** | **Display Format** | **ADR Ref** | **NIST** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| SESSION AND VOLUME |
| Total Actions — Today / 7-Day / 30-Day | Rolling counters from agent_actions. Baseline after 30 days of operation. | 3-number badge row | ADR-029 | AU-2 · SI-4 |
| Actions per Persona | Prototype / Automate / Research breakdown. Stacked bar shows relative load per persona. | Stacked bar chart | ADR-029 | AU-3 · SI-4(2) |
| Actions per Hour Heatmap | 7-day rolling heatmap (hour × day). Validates quiet hours enforcement 7pm–7am. Should be zero in quiet window. | Heatmap grid | ADR-028 · ADR-029 | AC-12 · AU-6 |
| ROUTING AND TIER DISTRIBUTION |
| Tier Distribution — 1 / 2 / 3 / 4 | Percentage of calls routed to each tier. Phase 1 target: Tier 4 = 0%. Informs whether confidence thresholds (0.85 / 0.90) are well-calibrated. | Pie chart + percentages | ADR-003 · ADR-027 | AU-2 · AU-6(1) |
| Escalation Rate Trend | Tier 1→2 and Tier 2→3 escalation rates over rolling 30 days. Rising rate = recalibration signal. | Line chart 30-day | ADR-027 | AU-6 · SI-4(2) |
| Opus Usage Counter | Phase 1 target: zero. Any Opus call = hard alert + Telegram escalation. Track lifetime count. | Red badge if > 0, green if 0 | ADR-028 | AU-6(1) · SI-4(5) |
| Local vs Cloud Call Ratio | Percentage of calls resolved locally (Tier 1/2 Ollama) vs cloud (Tier 3/4 OpenRouter). Cost and privacy indicator. | Donut chart | ADR-021 · ADR-027 | SA-9 · SC-7 |
| COST TRACKING |
| Estimated API Spend — Today / 7-Day / 30-Day | Aggregated from estimated_cost field in agent_actions. Threshold alerts from ADR-028 ($1.00 per batch). | 3-number badge + trend arrow | ADR-028 · ADR-029 | AU-2 · SI-4(5) |
| Spend by Tier | Tier 3 Sonnet vs Tier 4 Opus cost split. Opus should remain $0.00 in Phase 1. | Stacked bar by tier | ADR-029 | AU-6(1) |
| Spend by Persona | Cost attribution per persona. Identifies high-spend agents. | Stacked bar by persona | ADR-029 | AU-6(1) |
| Cost Threshold Breaches | Count of actions that hit the $1.00 batch threshold and triggered Telegram escalation. | Counter + timestamps | ADR-028 | SI-4(5) |
| CIRCUIT BREAKER — ADR-027 |
| Circuit Breaker Hit Count — 24h / 7-Day | Threshold: 10 calls / 60 seconds. Each hit = runaway agent or calibration issue. Rolling counters. | Badge + trend | ADR-027 | SC-5 · SI-4(5) |
| Circuit Breaker Event Timeline | Per-event log: timestamp, persona, call rate at trip, model tier. Sparkline shows event distribution over time. | Timeline + event table | ADR-027 · ADR-029 | AU-6 · IR-4 |
| Token Volume per Session | Context window trimmer triggers at 8,000 tokens. Track trim events as a signal of prompt inflation. | Line chart per session | ADR-027 | SI-4(2) |
| Replay Buffer Utilization | Count of entries in 30-day replay buffer. Percentage of calls that have full context replay available. | Single number + % | ADR-027 · ADR-029 | AU-3(1) |
| OUTPUT VALIDATION — ADR-022 |
| Validation Verdict Distribution | Pass vs Block breakdown. For blocks: which of the 7 pipeline stages triggered (schema / safety / irreversibility / prompt-inject / cost / format / approve). | Donut chart by stage | ADR-022 · ADR-029 | SI-6 · SI-10 |
| Prompt Injection Detections | Count of prompt injection flags caught at validation. Any non-zero = immediate alert. Lifetime counter. | Red badge if > 0 | ADR-022 · ADR-030 | SI-3 · SI-4(5) |
| Irreversibility Score Distribution | Histogram of irreversibility scores for all actions in rolling 30 days. Visualizes how close to the approval threshold (score > 20) actions are clustering. | Histogram | ADR-022 · ADR-028 | AC-6 · AU-2 |
| Safety Check Blocks | Count of actions blocked at the safety stage of the 7-step pipeline. Track trend. | Counter + trend | ADR-022 | SI-3 · SI-4 |

# **6.  Approval and Workflow Metrics**

Source: PostgreSQL agent_actions table (ADR-029) and ~/openclaw/staging directory. Approval_status, approval_response, and resolved_at fields cover the workflow layer. Little Snitch event log covers the OS-level network layer.

| **Metric** | **Detail / Alert Threshold** | **Display Format** | **ADR Ref** | **NIST** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| OPERATOR APPROVAL GATE — ADR-028 |
| Pending Approvals Count | Open Y/N requests awaiting operator response. Alert if any pending request is > 25 min (approaching 30-min auto-NO timeout). | Badge + age of oldest request | ADR-028 | AC-12 · IR-4 |
| Approval Response Time Distribution | Histogram of operator response times. Identifies patterns in how close to the 30-min timeout responses occur. | Histogram | ADR-028 · ADR-029 | AU-6 · AC-12 |
| Auto-NO Events — 24h / 7-Day | Requests that timed out (30 min) and were auto-rejected. Indicates operator unavailability or miscalibrated irreversibility thresholds. | Counter + trend | ADR-028 | IR-4 · SI-4(5) |
| Quiet Hours Enforcement Events | Count of requests queued or blocked during 7pm–7am window. Should be non-zero only on active evening/night agent runs. | Counter + heatmap overlap | ADR-028 | AC-12 |
| Approval vs Rejection Ratio | Y responses vs N responses over rolling 30 days. High rejection rate = miscalibrated thresholds or misuse pattern. | Donut chart | ADR-028 · ADR-029 | AU-6 |
| STAGING DIRECTORY — ADR-028 |
| Staging Directory File Count | Files in ~/openclaw/staging awaiting operator review. Alert if count > 10 (backlog building). | Badge + age of oldest file | ADR-028 | SC-7(10) · IR-4 |
| Staging File Age Distribution | Oldest file in staging. Alert if any file is > 48 hours old — review backlog. | Single number (oldest age) | ADR-028 | IR-4 |
| NETWORK POLICY — ADR-030 |
| Policy Violation Attempts | Count of agent attempts to reach unlisted destinations. Any non-zero = immediate Telegram escalation. Lifetime counter by persona. | Red badge + destination log | ADR-030 | SC-7(5) · SI-4(4) |
| Session-Only Approval Grants | One-time destination exceptions granted by operator. Track to identify recurring needs that should become permanent allowlist entries. | Counter + destination list | ADR-030 | AC-20 · AU-6 |
| Little Snitch Block Events | OS-level blocks from Little Snitch deny-by-default policy. Separate from YAML policy layer — catches any attempt to bypass the agent layer. | Counter + trend | ADR-024 · ADR-030 | SC-7(5) · SI-4(4) |

# **7.  Security and Compliance Metrics**

Phase 1 metrics come from the macOS unified log, sshd_config checks, and direct file system verification. Phase 2 metrics are delivered by the compliance_monitor sub-agent (ADR-032) via scheduled Telegram reports. All Phase 2 entries correspond to NIST OPEN or PARTIAL gaps identified in the compliance mapping document.

| **Metric** | **Detail / Alert Threshold** | **Display Format** | **Phase** | **NIST** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| OS-LEVEL SECURITY — Phase 1 |
| SSH Login Events per Day | From macOS unified log. Alert on count > expected baseline (solo operator) or logins from unexpected Tailscale device. | Bar chart daily | Phase 1 | AC-17(1) · AU-12(1) |
| Sudo Events per Day | From macOS unified log. Admin account only. Alert on any sudo from dev or openclaw accounts. Note: hw_collector.py sudo invocations (scoped to /usr/bin/powermetrics) are expected and logged here. | Counter + timestamp log | Phase 1 | AC-6(9) · AU-12(1) |
| Account Modification Events | macOS unified log: account creation, deletion, password change. Alert immediately on any unexpected event. | Event log + alert | Phase 1 | AC-2(4) · AU-12(1) |
| FileVault Encryption Status | On/off. Alert immediately if FileVault is disabled — all data-at-rest protection lost. | Traffic light (green = on) | Phase 1 | SC-28 |
| Backup Last-Run Status | 7-day green/red table. Green = successful dump. Red = failed dump (also triggers Telegram alert per ADR-019). | 7-day status grid | Phase 1 | AU-4 · IR-8 |
| Backup Dump File Integrity | Verify most recent pg_dump file is non-zero bytes and can be listed. Catches silent write failures. | Badge (pass/fail) | Phase 1 | SI-7 · IR-8 |
| SSH Idle Timeout Status | Confirm sshd_config ClientAliveInterval is set (SC-10 gap). Alert if not configured. | Traffic light | Phase 1 | SC-10 |
| Docker Image Digest Pinning | Confirm all images in Compose file have pinned digest (@sha256:...). Alert on any image running without digest. | Badge per image | Phase 1 | SI-7(1) |
| WiFi Interface Status | Confirm WiFi is disabled or firewall-blocked (AC-18 gap). Alert if WiFi is active on headless system. | Traffic light (green = disabled) | Phase 1 | AC-18 |
| NIST COMPLIANCE STATUS — Phase 2 (compliance_monitor) |
| NIST Control Status Summary | MET / PARTIAL / OPEN count by family (AC, AU, CM, IA, IR, SA, SC, SI). Weekly update from compliance_monitor. | 8-row scorecard table | Phase 2 | AU-6(1) |
| Open Gap Count Trend | 12 OPEN gaps at baseline (March 2026). Track reduction over Phase 1 and Phase 2 actions. Goal: 0 OPEN by Phase 2 completion. | Line chart (target = 0) | Phase 2 | CA-7 |
| PII Scan Results — Daily | Scan agent_actions output fields for PII indicators (email, SSN, phone patterns). Alert on any hit. | Daily pass/fail badge | Phase 2 | AU-13 |
| Service Enumeration Delta | New LaunchAgents or services vs prior-month baseline. Alert on any new addition not in ADR record. | Delta count + diff table | Phase 2 | CM-7(1) |
| Behavioral Anomaly Score | Calls per session vs 30-day rolling baseline. Standard deviation alert on > 2σ deviation from normal. | Trend line + anomaly flags | Phase 2 | SI-4(2) |
| Weekly Cost and Routing Digest | Aggregate spend, tier distribution, escalation rate, circuit breaker hits. Delivered via Telegram by compliance_monitor. Addresses AU-6(1) open gap. | Formatted Telegram message | Phase 2 | AU-6(1) |

# **8.  Display Format Reference Guide**

Each metric in this ADR is assigned a recommended display format. The table below defines each format, its best use case, and example metrics from this framework.

| **Format** | **Best Used For** | **Example Metrics** | **Tool / Source** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Traffic Light | Binary OK / warning / critical states where threshold crossings matter more than trend. | Thermal pressure · Memory pressure · WireGuard status · FileVault · Opus usage (0 = green) | Stats (mac-stats.com) · Telegram badge |
| Speedometer Dial | Continuous gauges with alert-zone arc. Best for metrics with a clear safe operating range and a threshold that must not be sustained. | CPU temp · GPU temp · Fan RPM · Power draw · P-core % · Memory % | Stats (mac-stats.com) · hw_collector.py · hardware_metrics |
| Sparkline | Compact time-series showing trend without detail. Ideal for Telegram message embeds. | CPU temp 24h · API spend 7-day · Escalation rate 30-day · GPU memory per session | Stats (mac-stats.com) · Telegram chart |
| Bar Chart | Comparing discrete categories at a point in time or over a defined window. | Actions per persona · Spend by tier · Spend by persona · SSH logins by day | SQL → Telegram · compliance_monitor |
| Stacked Bar Chart | Comparing composition across categories — shows both individual and total. | Tier distribution per persona · Memory by process · ChromaDB by namespace | SQL → Telegram · dashboard Phase 2 |
| Donut / Pie Chart | Proportional composition where the parts-of-a-whole relationship is the key insight. | Local vs cloud call ratio · Validation verdict breakdown · Approval vs rejection ratio | SQL → Telegram · compliance_monitor |
| Histogram | Distribution shapes — clustering, outliers, long tails. Not the same as a bar chart. | Irreversibility score distribution · Approval response time · Calls per session | SQL → Telegram · compliance_monitor |
| Heatmap Grid | Hour × day patterns. Immediately reveals time-of-day behavior, quiet hours compliance, and anomalous off-hours spikes. | Actions per hour heatmap · Approval events by hour · Cost per hour | SQL → Telegram · dashboard Phase 2 |
| Timeline / Event Log | Sequential events where timestamp and ordering matter more than aggregation. | Circuit breaker events · Autorestart events · Policy violations · Backup status log | SQL · macOS unified log |
| 3-Number Badge Row | Quick rolling-window summary (Today / 7-Day / 30-Day) for high-level situational awareness. | Total actions · API spend · System load average · Backup count | Telegram natural language query |
| Status Grid Table | Multi-item pass/fail status where each item has a binary state and recency matters. | 7-day backup status · NIST control family scorecard · Docker image digest status | compliance_monitor · Telegram |

# **9.  Phase 1 vs Phase 2 Summary**

| **Phase** | **Metric Categories Available** | **Source** | **Trigger** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Phase 1 Setup Day | All infrastructure metrics (thermals, memory, CPU, storage, network, uptime). All agent_actions metrics (volume, routing, cost, circuit breaker, validation). All approval/workflow metrics. OS-level security checks (FileVault, SSH events, sudo events, backup status). | Stats (mac-stats.com) · macOS · PostgreSQL · SSH shell | Available from first agent run |
| Phase 1.5 (hw_collector.py) | Full 60-second-resolution hardware telemetry: CPU P/E-core utilization, GPU utilization, ANE power, temperatures, fan RPM, system power draw, unified memory history, swap events. 90-day PostgreSQL retention. Three pre-written presentation SQL queries. | hw_collector.py · hardware_metrics (ADR-034) · PostgreSQL | ~14 days post-setup. Deploy after core stack is confirmed stable. |
| Phase 2 compliance_monitor | NIST compliance status summary (weekly). PII scan results (daily). Service enumeration delta (monthly). Behavioral anomaly detection (daily). Weekly cost/routing Telegram digest. Open gap count trend tracking. Hardware alert digest from hardware_metrics (ADR-034). | compliance_monitor sub-agent · PostgreSQL · macOS unified log · hardware_alerts view | Phase 2 sub-agent deployment under Personal persona |

# **10.  Recommended Tooling**

*Hardware Layer — Live Display (Phase 1 · Setup Day)*

- Stats by exelban (mac-stats.com) — open-source, MIT-licensed, free. Menu bar monitor for thermals, memory, CPU (P-core / E-core color-coded), storage, network, fan, GPU, and sensors. Replaces iStat Menus. Install: brew install --cask stats. No persistent storage — live display only. Actively maintained; M5 sensor support added March 2026. Configure menu bar: CPU graph (P/E cores separate colors) + temperature badge + fan RPM + memory pressure + Tailscale network throughput.

- pmset — macOS power management tool. Query sleep settings, autorestart status, and historical power events. Unchanged.

- macOS Activity Monitor — process-level memory and CPU during development and troubleshooting. Not used for presentations. Unchanged.

*Hardware Layer — Persistent History (Phase 1.5 · ~14 days post-setup · ADR-034)*

- hw_collector.py — purpose-built Python scraper running as a LaunchDaemon under the dev account. Polls sudo /usr/bin/powermetrics every 60 seconds using cpu_power, gpu_power, thermal, ane_power, smc, and memory_stats samplers. Writes 17 metric fields to the hardware_metrics PostgreSQL table. Provides the persistent history, session-arc data, and presentation-quality SQL queries that MacPulse would have supplied commercially. Governed by a single scoped sudoers entry: dev ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/powermetrics.

- hardware_metrics table (ADR-034) — PostgreSQL table in agentdb under the dev account. 17 metric columns, 90-day full-resolution retention matching ADR-029. Alert view (hardware_alerts) pre-built for Phase 2 compliance_monitor integration. Backed up by the existing nightly pg_dump (ADR-019). Three pre-written presentation queries (hw_live, hw_24h, hw_alerts) maintained in hw_collector_setup.py.

*MacPulse** (**macpulse.app**) was evaluated during Session 9 planning and not adopted. Its historical data and session recording functions are replaced by hw_collector.py + **hardware_metrics** at zero cost. Stats (mac-stats.com) replaces **iStat** Menus for the live display layer at zero cost.*

*Agent Layer (Phase 1)*

- PostgreSQL direct queries via SSH — all agent_actions metrics are SQL aggregations. No additional tooling required at Phase 1.

- Telegram natural language queries — OpenClaw can answer structured questions against agent_actions on demand.

- macOS unified log (log show command) — SSH login events, sudo events, account modifications for OS-level security metrics. Also captures all hw_collector.py sudo invocations automatically (AC-6(9)).

*Compliance Layer (Phase 2)*

- compliance_monitor sub-agent (ADR-032) — scheduled queries, Telegram reports, behavioral anomaly detection. All inference local (Tier 1/2). Read-only. Irreversibility score ≤ 20 on all tools. Phase 2 integration with hardware_alerts view (ADR-034) adds daily hardware threshold breach digest to Telegram reporting, closing SI-4(5) gap.

- Phase 2 dashboard — PostgreSQL-backed web dashboard (tech stack TBD at Phase 2 planning) for visual chart rendering. Telegram remains the primary operator interface.

*Skill Layer — Custom Implementation Only (Phase 1)*

No community skills from ClawHub or any external registry are installed or approved without explicit operator approval. All agent skills are custom-built and locally owned by default.

Three community skills were evaluated during Session 10 (March 30, 2026) and rejected. security-check was rejected because the threat surface does not justify installation — the operator manually reviews all skill source before any install, and the stack installs no community skills by default. domain-trust-check was rejected because all Prototype and Automate persona scrape targets are fixed, curated government URLs (Federal Register, HHS, USDA, state legislature, NH municipal domains) — not dynamically discovered links from untrusted sources. The community web-search skill was rejected in favor of a custom local implementation that routes results through Tier 1 local inference before context injection, eliminating unnecessary token use and keeping all credential handling internal.

Approved custom skill:

- web-search-local — Research persona only. Queries the Brave Search API (free tier, 2,000 queries/month). Raw results are summarized by a local Tier 1 Ollama model before injection into agent context, capping context contribution at 200–400 tokens per query regardless of result set size. Maximum 5 results per query. Maximum 3 queries per session without explicit operator approval. Every call logged to agent_actions with query string, result count, and summarized output. Brave API key stored in environment variables under the openclaw account only.

Build-local-first principle: All new agent capabilities are implemented as custom skills before any community or third-party skill is evaluated. A community skill may only be considered if a local implementation is technically infeasible or disproportionately complex. Any community skill evaluation requires explicit operator approval before installation.

Token conservation principle: Skills and agent behaviors that generate non-critical token use — context inflation, redundant tool calls, speculative queries — are explicitly prohibited. Any proposed agent action with unclear token cost requires explicit operator approval before implementation. Local Tier 1 inference is always preferred over cloud escalation for skill-layer processing.

