## **12.7  Memory and Storage Utilization**

*Unified Memory — Per-Process Breakdown*

Format: Stacked bar. The Mac Studio M1 Max has 32GB unified memory shared by CPU and GPU. The 32B Ollama model consumes 18–20GB alone. This visualization makes remaining headroom immediately visible during model inference.

| **Process** | **Typical Usage** | **Peak Usage** | **Alert At** | **Notes** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Ollama (32B model active) | 18–20 GB | ~22 GB | > 24 GB | Tier 2 high — load on demand only. Unload after session. |
| Ollama (14B model active) | 8–9 GB | ~10 GB | > 12 GB | Tier 2 standard. Can run alongside Docker + PostgreSQL. |
| Docker (all containers) | 2–4 GB | ~5 GB | > 8 GB | PostgreSQL + ChromaDB + OpenClaw containers. |
| macOS system + OpenClaw | 4–6 GB | ~7 GB | > 10 GB | OS baseline. Does not include model weights. |
| Available Headroom | ~12 GB (32B) | ~8 GB (32B) | < 4 GB = alert | Any swap > 0 = over budget. |

*Storage Growth Tracker*

Format: Table with current size, 30-day growth rate, and projected fill date. SSD has 80% alert threshold (410GB). iCloud backup folder tracked separately against 5GB Telegram alert threshold (ADR-019).

| **Storage Location** | **Current Size** | **30-Day Growth** | **Alert Threshold** | **ADR** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| SSD Total (512 GB) | 187 GB | +12 GB / month | 410 GB (80%) | — |
| Mac-Mini-Backups (iCloud) | 1.4 GB | +146 MB / month | 5 GB (Telegram alert) | ADR-019 |
| PostgreSQL Data Directory | 842 MB | +80 MB / month | 5 GB (review trigger) | ADR-029 |
| ChromaDB Vector Store | 340 MB | +60 MB / month | 10 GB (advisory) | ADR-011 |
| Docker Image Cache | 14 GB | +2 GB / month | 30 GB (prune trigger) | ADR-026 |

## **12.8  Dashboard Implementation Roadmap**

*Phase 1 — Available from Setup Day (April 1, 2026)*

Live display via Stats (mac-stats.com) — open-source, free, Homebrew-installable. All agent-layer metrics from direct PostgreSQL queries via SSH.

| **Metric Category** | **Implementation** | **Tooling** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Traffic light status board | Stats menu bar — live ambient display. Telegram query for text version. | Stats · mac-stats.com |
| Sparklines — thermals / power / fan | Stats native sparkline mode. Configure P/E-core colors, temperature badge, fan RPM. | Stats · mac-stats.com |
| 3-Number badge rows | SELECT COUNT(*) FROM agent_actions WHERE created_at > NOW() - INTERVAL '24 hours' | PostgreSQL SSH |
| Tier distribution | SELECT model_tier, COUNT(*) FROM agent_actions — rolling 30 days GROUP BY model_tier | PostgreSQL SSH |
| Persona activity stacked bar | SELECT agent_persona, DATE(created_at), COUNT(*) FROM agent_actions — rolling 7 days | PostgreSQL SSH |
| Approval workflow queue | SELECT * FROM agent_actions WHERE approval_status = 'pending' | PostgreSQL SSH |
| Circuit breaker timeline | SELECT * FROM agent_actions WHERE action_type = 'circuit_breaker_hit' | PostgreSQL SSH |
| Backup status 7-day grid | SELECT * FROM backup_logs ORDER BY run_date DESC LIMIT 7 | PostgreSQL SSH |
| Memory / storage | Stats for live memory pressure. du -sh for storage directories. | Stats + SSH |
| OS security events | log show --predicate from macOS unified log. Captures hw_collector.py sudo invocations (AC-6(9)). | macOS unified log |

*Phase 1.5 — Hardware Telemetry Persistence (hw_collector.py · ADR-034 · ~14 days post-setup)*

Deploy after core stack is confirmed stable. Requires one sudoers entry scoped to /usr/bin/powermetrics. Setup commands in hw_collector_setup.py. Alias hw_live, hw_24h, hw_alerts in .bashrc before any demo.

| **Metric Category** | **Implementation** | **Tooling** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| CPU P/E-core utilization history | SELECT sampled_at, cpu_p_core_pct, cpu_e_core_pct FROM hardware_metrics ORDER BY sampled_at DESC | hw_collector.py + PostgreSQL |
| GPU utilization + ANE power history | SELECT gpu_active_pct, ane_power_mw FROM hardware_metrics — reveals inference load on GPU and Neural Engine | hw_collector.py + PostgreSQL |
| CPU + GPU temperature history | SELECT cpu_temp_c, gpu_temp_c FROM hardware_metrics — hardware_alerts view flags threshold breaches | hw_collector.py + PostgreSQL |
| Fan RPM + system power history | SELECT fan_rpm, system_power_mw FROM hardware_metrics — demo arc: inference session power spike + thermal recovery | hw_collector.py + PostgreSQL |
| Unified memory + swap event history | SELECT mem_used_gb, mem_free_gb, mem_swap_gb, mem_pressure FROM hardware_metrics | hw_collector.py + PostgreSQL |
| 24-hour summary — hw_24h alias | Hourly averages: P-core, GPU, ANE, temp, power, fan peak, swap events. Runs in < 100ms. | PostgreSQL SSH |
| Pre-demo alert check — hw_alerts alias | Threshold breach count and peak values over 24h. Target: all zeros before any presentation. | PostgreSQL SSH |

Phase 1.5 replaces MacPulse entirely at zero cost. All data lives in agentdb, backed up by nightly pg_dump (ADR-019).

*Phase 2 — compliance_monitor Sub-Agent (Post Phase 1 Stable)*

All inference local (Tier 1/2). All tools irreversibility score ≤ 20. Read-only operations only.

| **Metric Category** | **Frequency** | **Telegram Delivery Format** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| NIST compliance scorecard | Weekly | 8-row table: family / MET / PARTIAL / OPEN / score% |
| Open gap count trend | Weekly | Gap count + delta from prior week + trend direction |
| PII scan results | Daily | Pass/fail badge + count of hits if any |
| Weekly cost and routing digest | Weekly | Spend by tier + tier distribution + escalation rate + CB hits |
| Service enumeration delta | Monthly | List of added/removed LaunchAgents vs prior baseline |
| Behavioral anomaly detection | Daily | Calls per session vs baseline. Flag if > 2σ deviation |
| Hardware alert digest (ADR-034) | Daily | hardware_alerts view: threshold breaches in last 24h. Closes SI-4(5) gap. |
| Account modification event summary | Weekly | Count of macOS account events. Alert on unexpected changes. |
| Docker image digest drift check | Weekly | Pass/fail per image. Flag any image without pinned digest. |

*Section 12 merged from standalone Dashboard Metrics Visual Reference document. March 30, 2026.*